     In Between the World and Me (2015), Ta-Nehisi Coates asserts, &quot;Slavery is not an indefinable mass of flesh.&quot; This course&mdash;Imagining American Slavery&mdash;considers what is definable about American slavery as imagined over time in the creative arts. Examining works of history, fiction, and film, students will read and analyze depictions of the &quot;peculiar institution&quot; to uncover connections between America&#39;s racial past and its racial present. Beginning with the narratives of Douglass and Jacobs, students will think with what Saidiya Hartman calls the &ldquo;afterlife of slavery&rdquo; and Rinaldo Walcott identifies as &ldquo;the long emancipation.&rdquo; In doing so, they will make connections between mass incarceration, civil rights, Black politics, Black creativity, and institutional barriers to Black freedom and aspirations, all within the historical context of the disposability/devaluing of Black life. We will explore the relationship between what Robin Kelley has called &quot;freedom dreaming&quot; and the imagination in defining and depicting slavery in the US.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Specific discussion topics may include the material conditions of American slavery; the emancipatory narrative and the liberatory narrative; pro-slavery ideology; abolition; regionalism; the archive; repetition and representation; constructions of racial identity; gender and slavery; memory and history; agency and resistance; and the idea and construct of freedom. Weekly readings, viewings, and writings will be required. The works we examine may include the following writers and artists: F. Douglass, H. Jacobs, J.W. Johnson, K. Chopin, M. Mitchell, W. Cather, O. Butler, S.A. Williams, T. Morrison, V. Martin, D. Bradley, L. Cary, H. Gerima, J. Peele, T. Coates, Q. Tarantino, S. McQueen, K. Lemmons, and J.C. Cooper.

    In August, 2023, Dakar, Senegal witnessed a tragic yet all-too-familiar situation that garnered significant media attention. A group of migrants embarked on a perilous voyage aboard a pirogue, with the goal of reaching the shores of Spain. Tragically, their overcrowded boat capsized, resulting in the loss of many young lives and once again leaving Senegalese society in shock. In West Africa, hundreds, if not thousands, undertake this hazardous journey each year, driven by an unyielding determination encapsulated by the Wolof phrase Barsa Wala Barsak, which translates to &quot;Barcelona, or Death.&quot; The experience of migration, whether coerced or voluntary, has been a central theme in the cultural production of Francophone Africa south of the Sahara. It serves as a compelling gateway to delve into the examination of African diasporic subjectivity and experience as depicted in the literature, cinema, and art of the region.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This course aims to investigate the plural motivations behind people&rsquo;s decisions to migrate, whether by choice or out of necessity, as well as the tangible and subtle consequences of these journeys on their self-perceptions, identities, cultures, and on the societies they leave behind. It also delves into how history and memory exert influence on individual and collective experiences of displacement and migration. To achieve this goal, the course will provide a thorough examination of the historical, political, and societal factors that contribute to a nuanced understanding of the diverse and distinct narratives of migration, displacement, and the resulting feeling of alienation or unbelonging often associated with such journeys in Francophone African contexts.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Students will engage with a curated selection of post-independence Sub-Saharan African literature, including novels, short stories, and poetry. Additionally, they will explore cinematic productions, photographic installations, music, and various artworks that grapple with themes such as voluntary mobility, the (dis)illusions of coveted migration, or traumatic displacement. Moreover, students will be introduced to a collection of scholarly and theoretical readings, as well as a number of contemporary news articles, to equip them with the necessary tools to refine their understanding of diasporic experiences and identities, as well as the crucial role of crossings (broadly understood) in their shaping. Together, we will thus critically analyze the mechanisms and forces that have molded the contemporary Francophone African diasporic subjectivity, exploring the diverse modes of its expression through art, film, and literature.

    This course is the second half of the two-part course sequence at Level III.  The course is designed to provide students thorough exposure to contemporary historical and social issues in Germany from 1945 to the present.  In Advanced II, the students explore the following two themes:

&bull; Fall of the wall and its consequences 
&bull; Germany: en route to a multi-cultural society

Drawing on the dual meaning of the German word Geschichte (i.e., history and story), the theme-oriented instructional units in Level III emphasize personal and public stories in German history, while connecting oral narratives with written narratives.  Students improve their ability to narrate, compare and contrast and establish causal relationships in speaking and writing. Through the integration of all modalities, this course promotes accuracy, fluency and complexity in language use. The development of advanced reading and writing is considered the primary means for expanding students&#39; language abilities at this level of language instruction.

By the end of Level III, students will
&bull; have an understanding of post-war historical events and of contemporary life in Germany; 
&bull; know how to approach authentic materials (television, news programs; videos) and use acquired knowledge to discuss and understand related issues;
&bull; produce paragraph-length dialogue, moving from the personal to the public narrative and to the formulation of argument and critical analysis in a formal setting;
&bull; possess knowledge of phrases necessary to engage in  meaningful interactive discussion;
&bull; read non-fiction and literary texts independently; 
&bull; improve their writing abilities through regular composition assignments 
&bull; possess strategies for vocabulary building and reading.

    In the intensive track, the two-course sequence of Level III is taught in one semester. The course is designed to provide students thorough exposure to contemporary historical and social issues in Germany from 1945 to the present.  In Intensive Advanced, the students explore the following four themes:

&bull; Germany after 1945: end of war, division of Germany, rebuilding the country
&bull; Two German states (1949-1989)
&bull; Fall of the wall and its consequences 
